  "prompt": "Why is mercury in a thermometer red?",
  "response": "Mercury itself is a silvery-gray liquid metal and does not appear red. However, many thermometers use a red dye added to the mercury to enhance visibility. The red color helps users easily read the temperature scale, making it more noticeable against the scale markings on the thermometer. This practice is common in various types of thermometers, including clinical and laboratory thermometers, to ensure that the temperature reading is clear and easy to interpret.",
